      "content": "My apologies, I seem to have gotten a bit carried away with my internal monologue about small, mischievous creatures! You are absolutely right to focus on the technical risks, and I will certainly keep the goblin chatter to a minimum for the sake of clear maintenance discussion.\n\nTo get back to the technical risks of blockages, the primary causes are indeed dust, insects, and ice. Dust accumulation is a slow, insidious problem, often exacerbated by poor environmental conditions or ground operations where debris is kicked up. Insects, while less common than dust, can cause sudden, catastrophic blockages if they manage to enter the tube. Ice formation is a meteorological risk, where supercooled water droplets freeze inside the tube, creating a solid obstruction.\n\nThese blockages are critical because they directly feed false or zero data into the airspeed indicator. If the tube is blocked, the pitot tube cannot measure the dynamic pressure of the oncoming air, meaning the pilot loses their primary reference for safe flight envelopes. It's a critical failure point, much like if a particularly clumsy goblin managed to jam the main lever on a very important, very delicate piece of machinery.",
